issue.title: GMM compatibility and usability fixes
issue.body:
Closes #321
Closes #324 
Closes #331

#### What does this implement/fix? Explain your changes.
- Fixes cosine similarity handling when a row is 0, in this case, cosine similarity is skipped and a warning is thrown
- Fixes deprecation warnings for Gaussian mixture by doing proper import 
- Masks convergence warnings internally in AutoGMM since regularization is increased when first attempts don't converge

issue.title: Tutorials: Meta-Issue
issue.body:
If nobody minds, I decided to make a list of all tutorial that exist and don't yet, and mark which need to be updated/created. I was a little confused by the multitude of issues, and I have a feeling that I am not the only one. @bdpedigo , please feel free to edit this post as you like.

- Models
  - Random Graph Models
  - (Eventually merge with simulations.)
    - [ ] Needs to be modified; see #368 for more information on merging models and simulations.
- Simulations
  - Erdos-Renyi (ER) Model
  - Stochastic Block Model (SBM)
  - Random Dot Product Graph (RDPG) Model
  - Correlated Graph Pairs
  - Correlated Random Dot Product Graph (RDPG) Graph Pair
- Embedding
  - Adjacency Spectral Embed
  - Embedding Multiple Graphs (aka OMNI?)
  - MASE
    - [x] Needs to be created; see #244. Claimed by @pauladkisson.
  - Advanced tutorial: Omni vs. MASE.
    - [ ] Needs to be created; see #444. Claimed by @PerifanosPrometheus.
  - Advanced tutorial: ASE vs LSE vs N2V.
    -  [ ] Needs to be created; see #401 (needs a separate issue?)
- Inference
  - Latent Position Two-Graph Testing
  - Latent Distribution Two-Graph Testing
    - [x] Needs to be modified; see #177. Claimed by @kareef928.
- Plotting
  - Heatmap: Visualizing a Graph
  - Gridplot: Visualize Multiple Graphs
  - Pairplot: Visualizing High Dimensional Data
- Matching
  - Introduction to Graph Matching
  - Seeded Graph Matching (SGM)
- Subgraph
  - Signal Subgraph Estimators
    - [ ] Will be modified & other algorithms added; see #120, #150, #305 & #349. Claimed by @caseypw . 
- Clusterings
  - All of them
    - [x] Need to be created; see #333. Claimed by @caseypw.
- Align
  - All of them
    - [x] Need to be created; see #414. Claimed by @Jingyan230. (probably downstream from #419 )
- Currently Miscellaneous
  - Regularization, P2R.
    -  [ ] Needs to be created; see #401 (needs a separate issue?)
  - Central Limit Theorem
    -  [ ] Needs to be created; see #442 (probably downstream from #378 )
  - The Embedding, the Alignment, and The LatentDistributionTest.
    - [ ] Needs to be created; see #443 (probably downstream from Align and LDT tutorials)

body:
@caseypw thanks for commenting with some DoD info. I'm going to ask everyone to do this in a week or two. 

For your DoD, I'd like more info. For example, can you sketch out what kind of simulations/results/metrics you'd like to have at a high level?

# Clustering Tutorial
## [Gclust](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688)
- Explain Gaussian Mixture Model
   - Math from Section 2.1 in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688) included in introduction and mathematics paragraph in markdown in notebook, explains all parameters
- Before each tutorial, explanatory paragraph in markdown describing why parameters are chosen and why they have specific default values.
- **Simulations**
   - Data identical to simulated data in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688): section 3.1.1
   - Tutorial Run 1: Default
     - `{min, max}_components` both set to default
     - `covariance_type`: 'all'
     - `tol`: 1e-3
     - `reg_covar`: 1e-6
     - `max_iter`: 100
     - `n_init`: 1
     - `init_params`: 'kmeans'
     - `random_state`: None
   - Tutorial Run 2: Random
     - `{min, max}_components` both set to default
     - `covariance_type`: 'all'
     - `tol`: 1e-3
     - `reg_covar`: 1e-6
     - `max_iter`: 100
     - `n_init`: 1
     - `init_params`: 'random'
     - `random_state`: None
   - Can also include these runs, but up to @bdpedigo @j1c :
     - With different `max_iter` value, discuss runtime effects of increasing this value
     - With different `{min, max}_components`
- **Metrics/Results**
   - Either comparable to paper and explain what was explained in paper
   - Or explain differences (method used, parameters, etc)

## [AutoGMM](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688)
- Explain Automated Gaussian Mixture Model
   - Math from Section 2.1 in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688) included in introduction and mathematics paragraph in markdown in notebook, explains all parameters and describes agglomerative clustering, mentions `gclust` tutorial notebook for reference.
- Before each tutorial, explanatory paragraph in markdown describing why parameters are chosen. Also explain why `max_components` is defaulted to 10 in `autogmm` but has no default value in `gclust`. Explain difference in function structure between `autogmm` and `gclust`.
- **Simulations**
   - Data identical to simulated data in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688): section 3.1.1
   - Tutorial Run 1: In-depth (verbose) default
     - `{min, max}_components` both set to default
     - `affinity`: 'all'
     - `linkage`: 'all'
     - `covariance_type`: 'all'
     - `random_state`: None
     - `label_init`: None
     - `max_iter`: None
     - `selection_criteria`: "bic"
     - `verbose`: 2
     - `max_agglom_size`: 2000
     - `n_jobs`: None
   - Tutorial Run 2: In-depth AIC
     - `{min, max}_components` both set to default
     - `affinity`: 'all'
     - `linkage`: 'all'
     - `covariance_type`: 'all'
     - `random_state`: None
     - `label_init`: None
     - `max_iter`: None
     - `selection_criteria`: "aic"
     - `verbose`: 2
     - `max_agglom_size`: 2000
     - `n_jobs`: None
  - Can also include these runs: 
    - Non in-depth versions of the same previous runs
    - {In, Not in}-depth with different `max_iter` value
    - {In, Not in}-depth with different `{min, max}_components`
    - {In, Not in}-depth with `label_init`
    - {In, Not in}-depth with higher `max_agglom_size`, discuss runtime effects of increasing this value
- **Metrics/Results**
   - Either comparable to paper and explain what was explained in paper
   - Or explain differences (method used, parameters, etc)

## [Kclust](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688)
- Explain Kmeans Cluster
   - Math from Section 2.1 in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688) included in introduction and mathematics paragraph in markdown in notebook, explains all parameters, describes difference from other clustering algorithms.
- Before each tutorial, explanatory paragraph in markdown describing why parameters are chosen. Explain difference in function structure from `autogmm` and `gclust`.
- **Simulations**
   - Data identical to simulated data in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688): section 3.1.1
   - Tutorial Run 1: Default
     - `max_clusters`: 1
     - `random_state`: None
   - Tutorial Run 2: Higher max cluster
     - `max_clusters`: 2
     - `random_state`: None
- **Metrics/Results**
   - Either comparable to paper and explain what was explained in paper
   - Or explain differences (method used, parameters, etc)
- Simulations for kclust can have different simulated data since paper mainly focuses on Gaussian Mixture Modeling
- For all three, will recreate Figure 1 in [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02688)
